00:03:33.750 --> 00:03:36.260
So we have a number of
different kinds of drums.

00:03:36.260 --> 00:03:38.720
We have a Kagan drum,
we have a Kidi drum,

00:03:38.720 --> 00:03:40.350
we have an atsemiru
[Assumed Spelling] drum,

00:03:40.350 --> 00:03:43.850
and as well as a gankogui,
which is the bell pattern

00:03:43.850 --> 00:03:45.440
that you hear prominently.

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:49.160
Just very briefly and
schematically all

00:03:49.160 --> 00:03:50.930
of these rhythms are
a little more complex

00:03:50.930 --> 00:03:52.890
than the way I'm going
to introduce them.

00:03:52.890 --> 00:03:54.810
They tend to be organized

00:03:54.810 --> 00:03:57.640
in what Western people would
understand is different metrical

00:03:57.640 --> 00:03:59.240
frameworks, okay?

00:03:59.240 --> 00:04:02.850
That means that the Kagan drum
would do something like this,

00:04:02.850 --> 00:04:04.570
and I'm just going to
ask you to take a look

00:04:04.570 --> 00:04:06.500
up at the board if you can.

00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:10.530
You can think of this as a
short, long, short, long,

00:04:10.530 --> 00:04:11.830
short, long, short, long.

00:04:11.830 --> 00:04:14.130
So Kagan, Kagan, Kagan, Kagan.

00:04:14.130 --> 00:04:18.200
Sort of in sense organizing things
in threes, one, two, three, one,

00:04:18.200 --> 00:04:20.000
two three, one, two,
three, one, two, three.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:23.510
At least from the perspective
of a Western ear.

00:04:23.510 --> 00:04:28.420
A drum like Kidi would be doing
something like, dit, do, dit, dit,

00:04:28.420 --> 00:04:35.340
do, dit, do, which is
organized a bit more like, okay?

00:04:35.340 --> 00:04:38.910
So something like that
before it repeats, right,

00:04:38.910 --> 00:04:42.830
which is in the West says something
like that would be one, two, three,

00:04:42.830 --> 00:04:47.120
one, two, three, as opposed to one,
two, three, two, two, three, okay?

00:04:47.120 --> 00:04:50.410
So we layer these two different
drums more or less differently.

00:04:50.410 --> 00:04:53.460
Now again both patterns are
more complex in practice,

00:04:53.460 --> 00:04:57.780
but this is their signature sort
of placement in which they work.

00:04:57.780 --> 00:05:02.360
The bell pattern that you hear
is a very common bell pattern,

00:05:02.360 --> 00:05:06.700
a 12-8 bell pattern, which I'm just
going to play now in slow motion

00:05:06.700 --> 00:05:11.200
so that you can hear that part of
the ensemble for special attention.

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:20.240
[bells] It's a seven-stroke
bell pattern, one, two,

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:22.410
three, four, five, six, seven.

00:05:22.410 --> 00:05:27.730
It happens in a field or in what we
might call proct [Assumed Spelling]

00:05:27.730 --> 00:05:31.800
time in a field of 12.

00:05:31.800 --> 00:05:41.260 position:56%
Subdivided as two plus two plus one,
two plus two plus two, plus one.

00:05:41.260 --> 00:05:46.800
Okay, so let me just
illustrate that this way, okay?

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:51.050
Um, bum, bum, ba, bum, bum, one,
two, one, two, one, one, two, one,

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:54.110
two, one, two, one, one, two, one,
two, one, one, two, one, two, one,

00:05:54.110 --> 00:05:56.510
two, one, two, one, one,
that kind of thing, okay?

00:05:56.510 --> 00:06:02.050
I want to just draw that one up
in notation to give you an example

00:06:02.050 --> 00:06:07.370
of a striking, what we
might call a correlation

00:06:07.370 --> 00:06:11.840
between an African practice and a
Western technical instrument, okay?

00:06:11.840 --> 00:06:14.650
We've got one, two, one, two,
one, one, two, one, two, one,

00:06:14.650 --> 00:06:16.160
two, one, two, one, okay?

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:18.550
Everybody sort of get
the notation, right?

00:06:18.550 --> 00:06:21.100
For those of you in the back
it's not crucial and try to work

00:06:21.100 --> 00:06:25.050
with the ear, but visually
I put it this way

00:06:25.050 --> 00:06:28.040
because what's striking
about it is two things.

00:06:28.040 --> 00:06:31.490
The first is that there's
two longs, a short,

00:06:31.490 --> 00:06:34.230 position:56%
then three longs and a short, right?

00:06:34.230 --> 00:06:38.040
So there's something a little
asymmetric about this, right?

00:06:38.040 --> 00:06:40.430
In other words, when
you have a field of 12

00:06:40.430 --> 00:06:41.960
and we have 12 pulses here.

00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:48.330
Why? Because we have that and then
there's a space, space, space.

00:06:48.330 --> 00:06:53.110
If I count up the dots
I get 12 micro pulses

00:06:53.110 --> 00:06:55.900
against which seven are struck.

00:06:55.900 --> 00:07:00.780
So we have seven elements in a
field of 12, that's clock time

00:07:00.780 --> 00:07:04.460
for which seven stand out
for special attention, okay?

00:07:04.460 --> 00:07:07.330
The relationship of seven and
12, think of days of the week,

00:07:07.330 --> 00:07:10.130
think of the annual way
in which we organize time.

00:07:10.130 --> 00:07:14.580
This is something that is
contemplated a lot globally, okay?

00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:16.550
But the thing that I want
to draw your attention to is

00:07:16.550 --> 00:07:18.680
by being a little bit
asymmetrical we can sort

00:07:18.680 --> 00:07:21.620
of split the pattern
into two halves.

00:07:21.620 --> 00:07:26.530
The first half, which is long,
long, short, and the second half,

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:28.120
which has the three
longs and a short.

00:07:28.120 --> 00:07:31.610
In other words, the
boundaries happen

00:07:31.610 --> 00:07:34.570
in a slightly asymmetrical
way, okay?

00:07:34.570 --> 00:07:39.040
So with 12 you can multiply and
subdivide and so on into three

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:44.150
by four, four by three, six by two,
two by six, or which is important

00:07:44.150 --> 00:07:47.560 position:56%
because it can do all those
things, but it can do another thing,

00:07:47.560 --> 00:07:53.510
which is common in African music
which is to say you take your 12,

00:07:53.510 --> 00:07:57.490
you take your symmetry and then
you off center the symmetry by one.

00:07:57.490 --> 00:08:00.600
So you might call it N
minus one, N plus one.

00:08:00.600 --> 00:08:04.940
So if we've got 12, six plus
six, now we have six minus six,

00:08:04.940 --> 00:08:08.140
six plus six, five
plus seven, right?

00:08:08.140 --> 00:08:11.470
And if we count up the dots,
one, two, three, four, five,

00:08:11.470 --> 00:08:14.180
and then one, two, three,
four, five, six, seven --

00:08:14.180 --> 00:08:17.900
I should have put another dot
in here, ran out of paper --

00:08:17.900 --> 00:08:20.040
we have exactly that structure.

00:08:20.040 --> 00:08:22.540
Now just something to
bear in mind here is

00:08:22.540 --> 00:08:26.520
that this is not just a rhythmic
structure, but if you were

00:08:26.520 --> 00:08:30.880
to put this into a pitch field,
in other words, A, B, C, D, E, F,

00:08:30.880 --> 00:08:34.120
like on a piano, we get
exactly the structure

00:08:34.120 --> 00:08:37.530
of the modern piano, right?

00:08:37.530 --> 00:08:40.870
Instead of long we have a
tone, so it's long, long,

00:08:40.870 --> 00:08:43.530
short, long, long, long, short.

00:08:43.530 --> 00:08:45.860
We have a tone, tone,
half tone, half tone,

00:08:45.860 --> 00:08:47.510
tone, tone, tone, half tone.

00:08:47.510 --> 00:08:50.150
It's the white notes
on the piano, okay?

00:08:50.150 --> 00:08:54.840 position:56%
If I were to fill in the green
notes, we'll confuse colors tonight,

00:08:54.840 --> 00:08:58.840
that is the black notes
on the piano, okay?

00:08:58.840 --> 00:09:00.580
Something to think about why?

00:09:00.580 --> 00:09:04.220
Because the piano is designed in
such a way, in the 18th Century

00:09:04.220 --> 00:09:05.520
when they sort of came

00:09:05.520 --> 00:09:09.160 position:56%
to standardize the modern industrial
piano it's designed in such a way

00:09:09.160 --> 00:09:13.050
that it's capable of
very easily modulating

00:09:13.050 --> 00:09:16.550
from one pitch area
to another, okay?

00:09:16.550 --> 00:09:21.100
So you can move from C major to,
say, G major with very little --

00:09:21.100 --> 00:09:24.230
with tweaking the system
just a little bit.

00:09:24.230 --> 00:09:27.880
In time you can also
modulate from one place

00:09:27.880 --> 00:09:30.950
to another place fairly easily, and
I'll explain that in more detail

00:09:30.950 --> 00:09:34.800
as we get into this
lecture a little later.

00:09:34.800 --> 00:09:38.130
So that is an important sort of
feature and common characteristic

00:09:38.130 --> 00:09:41.350
that it has as a mathematical
structure that incarnates

00:09:41.350 --> 00:09:45.540
in African rhythmic practice
as a timeline pattern

00:09:45.540 --> 00:09:49.260
and in Western practice as a
technical device for music making,

00:09:49.260 --> 00:09:51.630
which has been, you know,
had a great monopoly

00:09:51.630 --> 00:09:53.830
of thinking and music in the West.

00:09:53.830 --> 00:09:56.490
Not an insignificant
instrument, the piano,

00:09:56.490 --> 00:09:58.600
especially if we consider
its afterlife

00:09:58.600 --> 00:10:00.930
in MIDI [Assumed Spelling],
which is a software

00:10:00.930 --> 00:10:05.120
that basically incarnates the
assumptions of the piano into code.

00:10:05.120 --> 00:10:10.110 position:56%
Okay, so these are just some of the
features that I want you to remember

00:10:10.110 --> 00:10:13.100
as we move on through this lecture.

00:10:13.100 --> 00:10:16.590
That we have here a sense
of staggered downbeats,

00:10:16.590 --> 00:10:17.890
different rhythmic cycles

00:10:17.890 --> 00:10:21.290
that we can say have a
different kind of downbeat.

00:10:21.290 --> 00:10:27.340 position:56%
We have the principle of N minus
one or N plus one, asymmetry, right?

00:10:27.340 --> 00:10:29.150
And we have another
principle that I just want

00:10:29.150 --> 00:10:32.950
