position and find yourself?

01:03:11.560 --> 01:03:15.750
Well, consider that the two ways,

01:03:15.750 --> 01:03:20.080
the ways in which you can
order two elements in a field

01:03:20.080 --> 01:03:23.530
of three would include, let's
say longs and shorts, okay?

01:03:23.530 --> 01:03:28.430
We could have three longs,
we could have three shorts.

01:03:28.430 --> 01:03:30.120
Everybody with me?

01:03:30.120 --> 01:03:36.290
You could have two longs and a
short and then we have to recognize

01:03:36.290 --> 01:03:38.790
that there are three
ways of ordering that.

01:03:38.790 --> 01:03:44.900
Long, short, long and
short, long, long, right?

01:03:44.900 --> 01:03:46.600
So we have three longs over here.

01:03:46.600 --> 01:03:50.070
Here we have two longs and a
short, so we go long, long, short.

01:03:50.070 --> 01:03:51.370
Long, short, long.

01:03:51.370 --> 01:03:52.670
Short, long, long.

01:03:52.670 --> 01:03:53.970
Just spelling it out.

01:03:53.970 --> 01:03:56.710
The other third permutation would
be having two shorts and a long.

01:03:56.710 --> 01:03:58.260
Let's just do the same thing.

01:03:58.260 --> 01:04:00.400
Short, short, long.

01:04:00.400 --> 01:04:04.070
And now we'll rotate
that in its threefold way

01:04:04.070 --> 01:04:06.310
and we get long, short, short.

01:04:06.310 --> 01:04:07.930
So short, short, long.

01:04:07.930 --> 01:04:09.230
Short, long, short.

01:04:09.230 --> 01:04:11.540
Long, short, short, okay?

01:04:11.540 --> 01:04:18.250
Notice that this is one, plus
three, plus three, plus one.

01:04:18.250 --> 01:04:20.730
It's two to the power of three,
which equals one, two, three, four,

01:04:20.730 --> 01:04:24.560
five, six, seven, eight, okay?

01:04:24.560 --> 01:04:28.540
That's what's going on and these
are known as binomial coefficients.

01:04:28.540 --> 01:04:30.780
How would you encode that in sound?

01:04:30.780 --> 01:04:33.210
Well, let's take a
look at this pattern,

01:04:33.210 --> 01:04:37.430
let's just call it
off or three elements.

01:04:37.430 --> 01:04:41.790
The first three we can
call them long, long, long.

01:04:41.790 --> 01:04:46.970 position:56%
The second three, long, long, short.

01:04:46.970 --> 01:04:53.100
The next one, next three
is long, short, long.

01:04:53.100 --> 01:05:00.120
Let's go up here, the next
one is short, long, short.

01:05:00.120 --> 01:05:03.450
Then we have long, short, short.

01:05:03.450 --> 01:05:06.790
We have short, short, short.

01:05:06.790 --> 01:05:09.630
And then we have short, short,
and we've got to spin it

01:05:09.630 --> 01:05:18.940
around this side, long, and
finally short, long, long.

01:05:18.940 --> 01:05:23.830
One, two, three, four, five,
six, seven, eight groupings.

01:05:23.830 --> 01:05:26.030
And what are they?

01:05:26.030 --> 01:05:27.670
Long, long, long is over here.

01:05:27.670 --> 01:05:29.630
Short, short, short is over here.

01:05:29.630 --> 01:05:31.580
Long, long, short.

01:05:31.580 --> 01:05:36.440
You can figure it out, but
they're distributed right

01:05:36.440 --> 01:05:37.740
across that pattern.

01:05:37.740 --> 01:05:44.840
This means that as soon as you hear
any three pulses you are exactly

01:05:44.840 --> 01:05:47.790
precisely located within
that pattern.

01:05:47.790 --> 01:05:51.850
So your clappers are not just
sort of having fun and, you know,

01:05:51.850 --> 01:05:54.700
they're actually guiding
in a sort of metronomic way

01:05:54.700 --> 01:05:57.240
where you fit in to the pattern.

01:05:57.240 --> 01:06:02.010 position:56%
Given that a big conductor pulse
would just be absolutely disruptive,

01:06:02.010 --> 01:06:04.180
it would simply pick out one part

01:06:04.180 --> 01:06:11.230
of the performance that's
actually multi-metric.

01:06:11.230 --> 01:06:15.290
Let me skip this, but the composer,
Steve Rush [Assumed Spelling],

01:06:15.290 --> 01:06:18.560
actually took one of these similar
related pattern and turned it

01:06:18.560 --> 01:06:19.860
into minimalist -- it was one

01:06:19.860 --> 01:06:21.300
of the founding moments
of minimalist music.

01:06:21.300 --> 01:06:24.790
I'd be happy to entertain that
in question time, but let's --

01:06:24.790 --> 01:06:28.360
it circulates at this point
as an ethnographic text.

01:06:28.360 --> 01:06:32.010
He read a lot of transcriptions
through A.M. Jones,

01:06:32.010 --> 01:06:35.110
the Reverend Jones who had done a
lot of work in Africa and so on.

01:06:35.110 --> 01:06:38.200
There's a long story to be
told here about how things get.

01:06:38.200 --> 01:06:40.870
It's not just the Africarribean,
there's different stories,

01:06:40.870 --> 01:06:43.810
and I haven't done
that justice but I want

01:06:43.810 --> 01:06:46.330
to get you attuned to
some of the issues.

01:06:46.330 --> 01:06:49.460
In fact, he wrote that piece and
there's a sketch that he wrote

01:06:49.460 --> 01:06:51.310
and he considered it
to be too African,

01:06:51.310 --> 01:06:53.780 position:56%
he wanted it to sound more
original, but he nevertheless stayed

01:06:53.780 --> 01:06:55.080
with the African pattern.

01:06:55.080 --> 01:06:58.330
Why? Because in a permutation
setting you can't mess

01:06:58.330 --> 01:07:01.300
with these change of digit
and everything falls away

01:07:01.300 --> 01:07:03.660
and the interest is
considerably less.

01:07:03.660 --> 01:07:08.050 position:56%
So briefly I want to just talk about
African mathematics in general.

01:07:08.050 --> 01:07:10.540
I'm not an expert in
the entire field,

01:07:10.540 --> 01:07:14.460 position:56%
but I do want to draw your attention
to it, just a couple of features

01:07:14.460 --> 01:07:16.820
of current research in this.

01:07:16.820 --> 01:07:20.820
Such as that into the
archaeological sort of remnants

01:07:20.820 --> 01:07:22.120
of mathematical practice.

01:07:22.120 --> 01:07:25.140
In other words, when did
we as a species begin

01:07:25.140 --> 01:07:29.160
to think mathematically, like when
is the first baboon fibula not used

01:07:29.160 --> 01:07:31.400
as a tool but used
as a counting device?

01:07:31.400 --> 01:07:36.100
And the oldest ones emerge as
expected, in my view, from Africa.

01:07:36.100 --> 01:07:37.400 position:56%
This eshongo [Assumed Spelling] bone

01:07:37.400 --> 01:07:40.090
that you see here is
8,000 years old.

01:07:40.090 --> 01:07:42.930
There's an argument about whether
it's 9,000 or 7,000, you know,

01:07:42.930 --> 01:07:45.060
it's not my debate, but
it's a long time ago

01:07:45.060 --> 01:07:49.210
and it predates a lot
of numeric thinking.

01:07:49.210 --> 01:07:51.840
There's also the Lebombo [Assumed
Spelling] bone in South Africa.

01:07:51.840 --> 01:07:54.310
What I just want to draw
your attention to is not only

01:07:54.310 --> 01:07:57.870
like if you look at the
markings that are on here,

01:07:57.870 --> 01:08:00.050
it's not just that we have
a prime quadrant on the left

01:08:00.050 --> 01:08:04.670
which equals 60, we have certain
kinds of ratios in the middle,

01:08:04.670 --> 01:08:06.020
and you can figure those out.

01:08:06.020 --> 01:08:09.330
But this one interests me
because it's 11, 21, 19 and nine.

01:08:09.330 --> 01:08:13.450
This looks like decimalism in the
form of N minus one, N plus one,

01:08:13.450 --> 01:08:17.380
to me, but I can just speculate
at this point about how that kind

01:08:17.380 --> 01:08:22.060
of thinking gets to be
amongst us as a species.

01:08:22.060 --> 01:08:27.580
Okay, so I want to end with two
more genres of music to really get

01:08:27.580 --> 01:08:31.600
down more seriously into the way

01:08:31.600 --> 01:08:35.690
in which African patterns
articulate very interesting

01:08:35.690 --> 01:08:37.070
mathematical worlds.

01:08:37.070 --> 01:08:40.350
Remember I talked about shifting
and shaping or being off the beat

01:08:40.350 --> 01:08:43.610
or turning the beat around, and
the other one extending the beat.

01:08:43.610 --> 01:08:46.820
In Africa there are
considerable traditions

01:08:46.820 --> 01:08:48.570
that do both of these things.

01:08:48.570 --> 01:08:53.030
I want to turn you now to
a kind of a region called,

01:08:53.030 --> 01:08:58.180
today called Uganda, that in
some sense is a tragic place

01:08:58.180 --> 01:09:01.440
because when Motona Bota
[Assumed Spelling] came into power

01:09:01.440 --> 01:09:08.870
in 1961 I think it is they
soon after, he had the cabaco

01:09:08.870 --> 01:09:10.750
and the luberi [Assumed
Spelling] court sort

01:09:10.750 --> 01:09:14.800
of destroyed and terminated, right?

01:09:14.800 --> 01:09:18.220
The cabaco is the former
chief, as it were,

01:09:18.220 --> 01:09:21.290
it's a terrible word,
but cabaco, okay?

01:09:21.290 --> 01:09:25.940
And in this court there was
considerable music played, 24-7.

01:09:25.940 --> 01:09:29.810
It was a semi-urbanized area,
said to be the source of the Nile,

01:09:29.810 --> 01:09:32.350
there are competing
sources of the Nile,

01:09:32.350 --> 01:09:35.570
but it had a certain
kind of stature.

01:09:35.570 --> 01:09:38.190
It was in pre-Colonial times.

01:09:38.190 --> 01:09:42.450 position:56%
However, because of the way Colonial
rule works very often what you do is

01:09:42.450 --> 01:09:44.640
politics, we're in
the politics capitol,

01:09:44.640 --> 01:09:47.940
what you do is you amplify
some part of your enemy, right,

01:09:47.940 --> 01:09:50.150
you separate and divide and rule.

01:09:50.150 --> 01:09:53.350
In direct rule you give your
chieftans a little more power

01:09:53.350 --> 01:09:57.250
than they might have had and then
they become corrupted in some sense

01:09:57.250 --> 01:10:01.000
or are seen later by the resistance
fighters as complicit, right?

01:10:01.000 --> 01:10:03.540
We have this debate
constantly at play.

01:10:03.540 --> 01:10:09.590
Unfortunately, this meant that
the complicit court was then ended

01:10:09.590 --> 01:10:12.480
and all the instruments were
burned and so on and so forth.

01:10:12.480 --> 01:10:14.410 position:56%
So it's a fairly tragic environment.

01:10:14.410 --> 01:10:18.500 position:56%
But, fortunately, there's some small
positive affects of Colonialism,

01:10:18.500 --> 01:10:19.800
if one can say it that way.

01:10:19.800 --> 01:10:22.080
And Hugh Tracy [Assumed
Spelling], who was commissioned

01:10:22.080 --> 01:10:26.410
to actually make recordings for the
Rhodesian Government at the time,

01:10:26.410 --> 01:10:28.000
kind of reeked out, a little bit

01:10:28.000 --> 01:10:30.030
like [inaudible] and
really got into it.

01:10:30.030 --> 01:10:31.790
He wasn't just doing
it as a job anymore,

01:10:31.790 --> 01:10:35.490
and discovered this great
universe of cultural making

01:10:35.490 --> 01:10:40.140
and made some recordings before
the luberi court was ended.

01:10:40.140 --> 01:10:45.010
And so we have a few
fragments of Hugh Tracy asking

01:10:45.010 --> 01:10:47.210 position:56%
to demonstrate how this music works.

01:10:47.210 --> 01:10:51.440
Now this is interlocking music, but
of a highly virtuosic character.

01:10:51.440 --> 01:10:55.010
What happens in this music is
that across a single xylophone,

01:10:55.010 --> 01:10:57.180
known as the amadinda
[Assumed Spelling],

01:10:57.180 --> 01:11:00.010
a performer will play
a certan pattern.

01:11:00.010 --> 01:11:03.460
Bong, bong, boo, be, bom, bom,
bom, bom, bom, bom, bom, bom.

01:11:03.460 --> 01:11:10.800
Very simple, but with octaves,
not what you might expect.

01:11:10.800 --> 01:11:12.510
And the reason is because
on the other side

01:11:12.510 --> 01:11:16.130
of the instrument another
performer is playing in the spaces

01:11:16.130 --> 01:11:19.550
of that first performer, a
pattern of a different length.

01:11:19.550 --> 01:11:24.260
So you're now nesting into
one pattern of another, right?

01:11:24.260 --> 01:11:28.720 position:56%
And this happens at very high speed,
sometimes 600 pulses per minute.

01:11:28.720 --> 01:11:31.140
This is very seriously high speed.

01:11:31.140 --> 01:11:34.080
And what happens as a
result is that because

01:11:34.080 --> 01:11:36.460
of this interaction
notice this is actually

01:11:36.460 --> 01:11:38.700
from Kubeka's [Assumed Spelling]
work, he made a depiction of this.

01:11:38.700 --> 01:11:41.400
Kubek is another interesting
Viennese scholar who went and moved

01:11:41.400 --> 01:11:44.590
to Africa and so on, settled there.

01:11:44.590 --> 01:11:48.100
He made this depiction
back I think it's in 1970s

01:11:48.100 --> 01:11:49.990
around his research,
goes back to the '50s.

01:11:49.990 --> 01:11:51.370
A very interesting guy.

01:11:51.370 --> 01:11:53.340 position:56%
Here is umwawuzi [Assumed Spelling],

01:11:53.340 --> 01:11:56.440
here is umwanazi [Assumed
Spelling] playing on opposite ends

01:11:56.440 --> 01:12:01.000
of this xylophone called the
amadinda [Assumed Spelling], right?

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:06.350
And what happens, of course, if
you play piano, think of two people

01:12:06.350 --> 01:12:09.680
on the opposite ends of a piano
playing within the same register

01:12:09.680 --> 01:12:11.810
and never touching
each other, right?

01:12:11.810 --> 01:12:14.150
You can't touch anyone because
technically you're going

01:12:14.150 --> 01:12:15.800
to dampen the wood, right?

01:12:15.800 --> 01:12:19.360
So you're always going to be off
when the other player is down,

01:12:19.360 --> 01:12:22.350
but you're occupying the same what
in music is called the register

01:12:22.350 --> 01:12:26.410
or the same area of
your keyboard, right?

01:12:26.410 --> 01:12:27.970
You're both coming
down in that same area.

01:12:27.970 --> 01:12:32.060
It's not like base and treble,
you're actually both in the middle.

01:12:32.060 --> 01:12:35.010
The music that comes to the
ear is radically different

01:12:35.010 --> 01:12:37.510
to the music that's
actually being played.

01:12:37.510 --> 01:12:42.550
The motor image of the performer
doing this is very different

01:12:42.550 --> 01:12:46.800
from the audial image, which
is construing this again using

01:12:46.800 --> 01:12:49.220
that phonic zelatrope
[Assumed Spelling] technique

01:12:49.220 --> 01:12:52.690
by putting patterns together
that are like phantom patterns.

01:12:52.690 --> 01:12:55.520
And these are taken out
by a third performer,

01:12:55.520 --> 01:12:56.820
umaqanazi [Assumed Spelling],

01:12:56.820 --> 01:12:59.240
and the part is called the
ookonira chunak [Assumed Spelling],

01:12:59.240 --> 01:13:02.350
and pulled out for
special attention as a kind

01:13:02.350 --> 01:13:04.620
of resultant or inherent pattern.

01:13:04.620 --> 01:13:07.560
So the concept of inherent
pattern or resultant pattern,

01:13:07.560 --> 01:13:09.790
which emerges in a lot
of Western composition,

01:13:09.790 --> 01:13:11.250
again of the avant-garde sort.

01:13:11.250 --> 01:13:13.200
I will not bore you
with those details,

01:13:13.200 --> 01:13:16.590
but that is actually an
African concept of ookonira,

01:13:16.590 --> 01:13:19.500
to bring something out that
nobody is playing, right?

01:13:19.500 --> 01:13:21.170
Take a listen to a short fragment,

01:13:21.170 --> 01:13:24.070
as I say these are compromised
recordings, very short,

01:13:24.070 --> 01:13:28.510 position:56%
didactic almost, at a long time ago.

01:13:28.510 --> 01:13:52.250
[ Music ]

01:13:52.250 --> 01:13:56.510
Your ear cannot follow that line,
it can only hear the results.

01:13:56.510 --> 01:14:03.040
[ Music ]

01:14:03.040 --> 01:14:04.710
And that's the knocking
brought out, the ookonira,

01:14:04.710 --> 01:14:07.510
where he's doubling
the resulting pattern.

01:14:07.510 --> 01:14:11.040
[ Music ]

01:14:11.040 --> 01:14:12.340
Okay, we'll stop that one there.

01:14:12.340 --> 01:14:16.620
Very briefly, the music gets even
more virtuosic with the akadinda,

01:14:16.620 --> 01:14:20.670
which is to say now you can
also sometimes place two beats

01:14:20.670 --> 01:14:23.420
within the space of one and so long

01:14:23.420 --> 01:14:25.350
as you never touch
the other performer.

01:14:25.350 --> 01:14:30.510
Take a listen to how this sounds
in its more virtuosic form.

01:14:30.510 --> 01:14:43.310
[ Music ]

01:14:43.310 --> 01:14:44.710
Second part will come in.

01:14:44.710 --> 01:14:46.280
So far so good.

01:14:46.280 --> 01:14:49.510
Now the spaces of the
spaces will be filled.

01:14:49.510 --> 01:15:01.060
[ Music ]

01:15:01.060 --> 01:15:02.860
Sometimes two beats, sometimes one.

01:15:02.860 --> 01:15:20.610
[ Music ]

01:15:20.610 --> 01:15:22.870
Okay, one wants to continue, okay?

01:15:22.870 --> 01:15:28.050
The very last music that
I want to introduce you

01:15:28.050 --> 01:15:29.890
to is that of the [inaudible].

01:15:29.890 --> 01:15:32.100
I've spent considerable
time with this music.

01:15:32.100 --> 01:15:34.610
I learned how to play this before
I learned how to play the piano,

01:15:34.610 --> 01:15:37.800
which is why I find the piano
so fascinating as you can tell.

01:15:37.800 --> 01:15:42.130
But here it is and this is the last
of the points I'm going to make,

01:15:42.130 --> 01:15:44.610
because I want to get
into what's actually going

01:15:44.610 --> 01:15:45.910
on in those inherent patterns?

01:15:45.910 --> 01:15:47.210
Right, where is the beat?

01:15:47.210 --> 01:15:50.140
It's very, very difficult for a
Westerner to place a beat there

01:15:50.140 --> 01:15:54.380
because in some ways the question
concerning the beat is itself put

01:15:54.380 --> 01:15:56.050
to question, right?

01:15:56.050 --> 01:15:58.190
And that's perhaps what's
at stake in this music,

01:15:58.190 --> 01:16:00.010
if you just hear water
flowing or something

01:16:00.010 --> 01:16:05.760
like that you're not doing enough
with your ears to open them

01:16:05.760 --> 01:16:07.900
to this field of possibility.

01:16:07.900 --> 01:16:13.300
Okay, here are what one might call
three keyboard interface designs,

01:16:13.300 --> 01:16:14.600
right?

01:16:14.600 --> 01:16:16.590
How is the technology designed?

01:16:16.590 --> 01:16:20.090
And the reason I take this as a
very interesting starting point

01:16:20.090 --> 01:16:23.790
for thinking through history
and thinking through math is

01:16:23.790 --> 01:16:27.500
because in some ways once the
interface design gets settled

01:16:27.500 --> 01:16:31.900
into a fixed structure it
carries a kind of history

01:16:31.900 --> 01:16:34.130
and it doesn't get
changed as quickly.

01:16:34.130 --> 01:16:36.540
When things become standardized
it tells you something

01:16:36.540 --> 01:16:39.270
about that culture and
how it standardizes,

01:16:39.270 --> 01:16:44.510
how it construes the body,
right, as an interacting medium.

01:16:44.510 --> 01:16:48.170
So machine learning, all of
this, how is the body construed

01:16:48.170 --> 01:16:52.330
in relation to the machines
with which it interacts.

01:16:52.330 --> 01:16:53.630
We will always [inaudible].

01:16:53.630 --> 01:16:55.800
The point is not that there's
natural people over here

01:16:55.800 --> 01:17:00.250
and technological -- no, we
are always technological.

01:17:00.250 --> 01:17:03.980
We automate fire, we're
technological, we sit back, okay?

01:17:03.980 --> 01:17:06.910
We can watch things happen for us.

01:17:06.910 --> 01:17:08.210
So this is not the point.

01:17:08.210 --> 01:17:10.260
The point is how do
different machines,

01:17:10.260 --> 01:17:15.940
how do different algorithms
comport the body in its behavior?

01:17:15.940 --> 01:17:21.020
So take, for example, Qwerty, the
typewriter, right, Q-w-e-r-t-y,

01:17:21.020 --> 01:17:22.320
where did that come from?

01:17:22.320 --> 01:17:23.620
Why Qwerty?

01:17:23.620 --> 01:17:27.060
This not how the piano is designed,
which is also a typewriter,

01:17:27.060 --> 01:17:30.600
it's a typewriter for sound, it's a
music inscription device that works

01:17:30.600 --> 01:17:35.850
like a phone, too, lots of
slices that make melodies.

01:17:35.850 --> 01:17:37.800
Why are typewriters
designed that way?

01:17:37.800 --> 01:17:40.570
They seem both efficient
and inefficient, right?

01:17:40.570 --> 01:17:42.480
They're inefficient
because you're kind

01:17:42.480 --> 01:17:43.910
of going back and forward, right?

01:17:43.910 --> 01:17:46.920
Why don't we just stroke through,
like t-h-e should be, you know,

01:17:46.920 --> 01:17:48.570
it shouldn't be like ta, ta, ta.

01:17:48.570 --> 01:17:50.210
Why is it back and forth?

01:17:50.210 --> 01:17:51.650
Why does that interlock?

01:17:51.650 --> 01:17:54.170
Because the hammers would
come flying into the same sort

01:17:54.170 --> 01:17:56.560
of end point, same focal point,
and you didn't want them jamming.

01:17:56.560 --> 01:17:59.740
So you don't want people playing
like a piano because the piano is

01:17:59.740 --> 01:18:01.770
in parallel hammers,
this is in hammers

01:18:01.770 --> 01:18:03.160
that all have the same destination.

01:18:03.160 --> 01:18:04.580
You didn't want that clogging up.

01:18:04.580 --> 01:18:06.610
So you build in an inefficiency

01:18:06.610 --> 01:18:08.800
and make sure you interlock
it a lot, right?

01:18:08.800 --> 01:18:10.400
So we get Qwerty.

01:18:10.400 --> 01:18:14.670
And then what happens is the theory
of ergonomics or whatever it was

01:18:14.670 --> 01:18:17.720
that the engineers were
working with have to take

01:18:17.720 --> 01:18:20.450
in account the 10 fingerishness
and then they have commitments

01:18:20.450 --> 01:18:22.250
about what these fingers can do.

01:18:22.250 --> 01:18:26.150
And the commitments are
usually these four in the West,

01:18:26.150 --> 01:18:29.500 position:56%
these four are really good,
they're facile, and this one is kind

01:18:29.500 --> 01:18:31.970
of bulky and stupid, maybe
it just has two, you know?

01:18:31.970 --> 01:18:36.040 position:56%
Whatever the reasons are, ergonomics
and so on, you construe these

01:18:36.040 --> 01:18:38.080
as being more facile or quicker.

01:18:38.080 --> 01:18:41.420
And so early pianism, the
piano, actually didn't even --

01:18:41.420 --> 01:18:44.400
eliminated the form, right,
you were supposed to do this.

01:18:44.400 --> 01:18:46.970 position:56%
Plus it emphasized righthandishness.

01:18:46.970 --> 01:18:51.110
So we have in the piano high
notes on the righthand side,

01:18:51.110 --> 01:18:52.720
low notes on the left-hand side.

01:18:52.720 --> 01:18:59.280
The very sort of, how should we
say, scalar way of organizing pitch

01:18:59.280 --> 01:19:02.660
as well as time, but that's
a different issue, okay?

01:19:02.660 --> 01:19:04.080
So instead of the circular one

01:19:04.080 --> 01:19:06.990
or symmetrical one this
is a scalar one, right?

01:19:06.990 --> 01:19:10.660
So from left to right, it's
a kind of darkness over here.

01:19:10.660 --> 01:19:12.720 position:56%
And why did you put this slow stuff,

01:19:12.720 --> 01:19:14.380
why did you put the base
notes in the left hand?

01:19:14.380 --> 01:19:17.240
Because the argument was that
the left hands are slower

01:19:17.240 --> 01:19:18.730
because we're all righthanded.

01:19:18.730 --> 01:19:21.160
Well, I mean that's the
sort of bias of technology.

01:19:21.160 --> 01:19:23.760
One needs to look at the values
built into technological designs

01:19:23.760 --> 01:19:25.770
because if you happen to be
lefthanded it's tough luck, okay,

01:19:25.770 --> 01:19:28.600
because there ain't that
much music that really --

01:19:28.600 --> 01:19:32.040
that's not entirely true,
but generally slow movement

01:19:32.040 --> 01:19:33.950
in the left hand and
then faster up here.

01:19:33.950 --> 01:19:38.490
And plus on typewriters it was
like the space bar, which was huge

01:19:38.490 --> 01:19:42.090 position:56%
and bulky, and you really eliminated
one, you didn't even need it,

01:19:42.090 --> 01:19:44.790 position:56%
but there seemed to be so transient,
you know, you can just hit

01:19:44.790 --> 01:19:47.060
that space bar easily
with the thumb, right?

01:19:47.060 --> 01:19:50.390
Same thing with pianism, it
comports the body in a certain way

01:19:50.390 --> 01:19:52.260
and then we respond
and we get really good

01:19:52.260 --> 01:19:54.100
at typing and playing piano.

01:19:54.100 --> 01:19:56.330
And so the model is, the engineers

01:19:56.330 --> 01:19:58.480
who are designing these systems
are flattered and they think, yes,

01:19:58.480 --> 01:20:01.170
we must have been right
about the body.

01:20:01.170 --> 01:20:02.560
So we are the order of complete

01:20:02.560 --> 01:20:05.520
for the incomplete
algorithm in some funny way.

01:20:05.520 --> 01:20:07.570
But what I want to draw
your attention to is

01:20:07.570 --> 01:20:12.860 position:56%
that that's not the only way of
designing music inscription devices.

01:20:12.860 --> 01:20:15.690
So if you just take look at the
metepa [Assumed Spelling] over here

01:20:15.690 --> 01:20:17.980
or the [inaudible] over
here, the difference is

01:20:17.980 --> 01:20:21.890 position:56%
that your low notes are more or
less in the middle of the instrument

01:20:21.890 --> 01:20:25.470
and the high notes fan
off to the side, right?

01:20:25.470 --> 01:20:28.400
So it's kind of reflective
of the symmetry

01:20:28.400 --> 01:20:30.890
or semi-symmetry of
the body, itself.

01:20:30.890 --> 01:20:34.070
I'm not arguing this is better,
it's just a different way

01:20:34.070 --> 01:20:37.960 position:56%
of organizing your digitorum, right?

01:20:37.960 --> 01:20:40.210
And what's interesting is,
I was going to bring it

01:20:40.210 --> 01:20:43.210
but it's too complicated to
sort of play in the context

01:20:43.210 --> 01:20:46.980
of this environment, but if you
were to play like a scale on this,

01:20:46.980 --> 01:20:49.180
because there's seven notes
before the octave recurs

01:20:49.180 --> 01:20:50.480
in this instrument.

01:20:50.480 --> 01:20:54.010 position:56%
You'd do something very strange,
you'd have to start here, jump here,

01:20:54.010 --> 01:20:57.110
jump all the way across there,
back there, back there, back there,

01:20:57.110 --> 01:21:01.290 position:56%
back there, back there, back there
to play just da, da, da, da, da, da.

01:21:01.290 --> 01:21:04.590
You'd be going -- it's
very cumbersome to play.

01:21:04.590 --> 01:21:06.100
However, jumping by a fifteenth

01:21:06.100 --> 01:21:09.380
or by octave is very
easy to play, okay?

01:21:09.380 --> 01:21:11.980
So it's construing the
sounding forms that come

01:21:11.980 --> 01:21:15.050
out of this interaction with
the body are very different

01:21:15.050 --> 01:21:16.350
as a result of that.

01:21:16.350 --> 01:21:20.630
No less facile, no less
eloquent and so on and so forth.

01:21:20.630 --> 01:21:24.730
The other important thing
about the mbira [inaudible] is

01:21:24.730 --> 01:21:27.940
that there's a division of labor
between two performers, right?

01:21:27.940 --> 01:21:33.140
So where one performer is playing
on the beat, the other player plays

01:21:33.140 --> 01:21:35.850
in the spaces of that beat, right?

01:21:35.850 --> 01:21:38.370
So this is not -- it's
like the amadinda,

01:21:38.370 --> 01:21:41.620
you don't play simultaneously,
you play

01:21:41.620 --> 01:21:44.630
and nest your performance
in this kind of way.

01:21:44.630 --> 01:21:48.050
So where you're on, the
other performer is off, okay?

01:21:48.050 --> 01:21:49.860
Let's listen to actually
