01:32:14.730 --> 01:32:19.040
a tradition that barely exists
anymore, to sonar patterns

01:32:19.040 --> 01:32:24.560
where you have to make your way
through a series or a gridded kind

01:32:24.560 --> 01:32:29.970
of set of matrix and then find
your way and create patterns

01:32:29.970 --> 01:32:31.920
of imagination and
so on and so forth,

01:32:31.920 --> 01:32:34.830
but they have to be
symmetrical in these ways.

01:32:34.830 --> 01:32:37.770
So it's a trick, it's a
trick, it's a math trick.

01:32:37.770 --> 01:32:41.480
This was actually a secret kind
of group, quite patriarchal,

01:32:41.480 --> 01:32:45.600
and so this is one of the tragedies
though of African mathematics

01:32:45.600 --> 01:32:49.910
because the way in which you got
important information was not

01:32:49.910 --> 01:32:52.390
necessarily through this
principle of copyright,

01:32:52.390 --> 01:32:57.290 position:56%
which is how one does it in the
West, but by abolishing all evidence

01:32:57.290 --> 01:32:58.830
so that you can retain authority

01:32:58.830 --> 01:33:00.650
within smaller kind
of secret societies.

01:33:00.650 --> 01:33:04.180
So it's one, it's an area
of great interest and also

01:33:04.180 --> 01:33:08.120
in some sense tragic because how
do we reconstruct these great

01:33:08.120 --> 01:33:10.920
mathematical traditions
when part of the project was

01:33:10.920 --> 01:33:12.760
to eliminate the archive?

01:33:12.760 --> 01:33:15.490
And in the West we can talk
about copyright as a way

01:33:15.490 --> 01:33:20.280
of giving authority to
certain voices and that, too,

01:33:20.280 --> 01:33:24.260
is a system that has great
affordance but also limits,

01:33:24.260 --> 01:33:26.930
there are serious limits,
especially if we look at how some

01:33:26.930 --> 01:33:29.260
of the biographies of
these sounds work, right?

01:33:29.260 --> 01:33:33.190
We have this music from
Africa that is authored there,

01:33:33.190 --> 01:33:34.490
but then when it's taken

01:33:34.490 --> 01:33:39.830
up by Western musicians suddenly
it becomes copyright worthy, right?

01:33:39.830 --> 01:33:43.060 position:56%
That's another very important
question, but I'll leave it at that.

01:33:43.060 --> 01:33:44.360
That's where that's from, Angola.

01:33:44.360 --> 01:33:47.830
Gerhart Kubek [Assumed Spelling]
writes about it beautifully.

01:33:47.830 --> 01:33:50.770
Gergli Legetti [Assumed Spelling],
who is a Western composer,

01:33:50.770 --> 01:33:54.120
also part of the avant-garde, he
was like a highly funded composer

01:33:54.120 --> 01:33:58.460
of Europe, drew great inspiration
from these diagrams, as well,

01:33:58.460 --> 01:34:02.480
when he Africanized
his piano techniques

01:34:02.480 --> 01:34:05.060
and that's a very interesting new
kind of piano sound that comes

01:34:05.060 --> 01:34:07.560
out of his because
of this encounter.

01:34:07.560 --> 01:34:08.860
Hi.

01:34:08.860 --> 01:34:11.520
&gt;&gt; Can you talk a little bit

01:34:11.520 --> 01:34:16.570 position:56%
about South African inspiration
[inaudible] where did ancestors come

01:34:16.570 --> 01:34:22.420
up with these rhythms [inaudible]
and everything around them,

01:34:22.420 --> 01:34:27.180
somewhere out in the bush,
an orchestra in itself.

01:34:27.180 --> 01:34:33.510
I'm just curious if there's things,
mathematical connection with things

01:34:33.510 --> 01:34:39.330
that are in nature that sequence in
with these rhythms that are used?

01:34:39.330 --> 01:34:41.780
&gt;&gt; Martin Scherzinger:
That's such a nice question,

01:34:41.780 --> 01:34:44.540
but it really is too
big for me to engage.

01:34:44.540 --> 01:34:46.400
And I have to say that
my focus is quite narrow.

01:34:46.400 --> 01:34:49.530
It's deliberately narrow
because of my own biography

01:34:49.530 --> 01:34:54.010
and my own biographical sort
of relationship to the land,

01:34:54.010 --> 01:34:59.190
which means I grew up in
Apartheid and one of the dangers

01:34:59.190 --> 01:35:04.060
of organizing people according
to cultural identities was

01:35:04.060 --> 01:35:06.820
that it very quickly
becomes hierarchized.

01:35:06.820 --> 01:35:11.720
So I felt very suspicious
about that from the beginning.

01:35:11.720 --> 01:35:17.140 position:56%
I could see in some sense as a child
unfolding before me great injustice

01:35:17.140 --> 01:35:21.610
simply because of the way people
were being understood to be.

01:35:21.610 --> 01:35:26.310 position:56%
And so for me understanding Africans
as having very connected to dance

01:35:26.310 --> 01:35:31.260
and embodied and so on was a way
of disavowing the intellectual work

01:35:31.260 --> 01:35:32.940
that was built into this.

01:35:32.940 --> 01:35:38.550 position:56%
So when the question of
environment comes up I'm a little --

01:35:38.550 --> 01:35:43.850 position:56%
I back off a little bit only because
of that, because it's the idea

01:35:43.850 --> 01:35:47.010
that people are more
natural or something.

01:35:47.010 --> 01:35:50.660
However, there's very
interesting work being done that.

01:35:50.660 --> 01:35:53.110
I mean Steven Feld [Assumed
Spelling] has done some very

01:35:53.110 --> 01:35:55.240
interesting work, looking

01:35:55.240 --> 01:35:59.320
at how soundscapes impact
how people organize time.

01:35:59.320 --> 01:36:02.880
And you know anybody
who has been to Africa,

01:36:02.880 --> 01:36:05.060
I mean it's an incredible
soundscape,

01:36:05.060 --> 01:36:09.530
and just the simple rhythms of
open space are something to behold.

01:36:09.530 --> 01:36:12.950
So it wouldn't surprise me if
there's some kind of connection.

01:36:12.950 --> 01:36:17.740
The archaeology and all of those
kinds of questions are extensive,

01:36:17.740 --> 01:36:20.170
you know, how tuning
systems emerged.

01:36:20.170 --> 01:36:22.710
Most of my work that I've done
in this region has nothing to do

01:36:22.710 --> 01:36:26.160
with rhythm, partly because
I shy away from the idea

01:36:26.160 --> 01:36:30.880
that Africans have a special
endowment for rhythm or something,

01:36:30.880 --> 01:36:32.770
and I use the pun intendedly

01:36:32.770 --> 01:36:35.680
because there's this
cliche that comes with it.

01:36:35.680 --> 01:36:39.040
In fact, [inaudible] music
is more noteworthy for me

01:36:39.040 --> 01:36:44.260
because of its profound harmonies
and the way harmony works

01:36:44.260 --> 01:36:47.670
through space, which is
a kind of fractal logic,

01:36:47.670 --> 01:36:49.570
which would have just been
a little too difficult

01:36:49.570 --> 01:36:51.220
for an open forum like this.

01:36:51.220 --> 01:36:53.470
It's a more strictly
mathematical set theoretical world

01:36:53.470 --> 01:36:56.950
and I would have had to start there
and I would have maybe got a point

01:36:56.950 --> 01:36:58.500
or two across in that time.

01:36:58.500 --> 01:37:03.360
So I didn't do it, but imagine
there's no rhythm in African music,

01:37:03.360 --> 01:37:05.510
imagine there's no dance,
and now you're just left

01:37:05.510 --> 01:37:11.590
with certain tuning practices
and harmonies and you get results

01:37:11.590 --> 01:37:15.790
that are even more
mathematically compelling.

01:37:15.790 --> 01:37:17.830
I'd be happy again to talk right

01:37:17.830 --> 01:37:20.570
after if you're interested
in that part.

01:37:20.570 --> 01:37:26.970 position:56%
So I was always drawn to how this
music is thought because the people,

01:37:26.970 --> 01:37:32.300
you know, we were raised in
interesting ways in South Africa.

01:37:32.300 --> 01:37:39.440
I was raised by partly by my
older sister and a maid, right,

01:37:39.440 --> 01:37:43.660
so I didn't ever understand this
as being a kind of distinction,

01:37:43.660 --> 01:37:50.470
that I was encouraged to in the
classroom, in our education system.

01:37:50.470 --> 01:37:55.200
Of course, I benefitted
from white education,

01:37:55.200 --> 01:38:01.560
but at the same time my cultural
wires got a little crossed.

01:38:01.560 --> 01:38:03.520
I forget who, was it you, sorry?

01:38:03.520 --> 01:38:06.540
&gt;&gt; The last recording
that you played you had

01:38:06.540 --> 01:38:09.450
on the screen a picture of I
guess a finger piano, a kalimba,

01:38:09.450 --> 01:38:11.630
and you called it a solo,
was that a single person?

01:38:11.630 --> 01:38:12.930
&gt;&gt; Martin Scherzinger: Yes.

01:38:12.930 --> 01:38:14.230
&gt;&gt; Playing a single instrument?

01:38:14.230 --> 01:38:15.530
&gt;&gt; Martin Scherzinger: Yes,

01:38:15.530 --> 01:38:19.320
so that's Gwanzuto Gwenzie [Assumed
Spelling], a remarkable player,

01:38:19.320 --> 01:38:25.110 position:56%
absolutely remarkable player, who is
basically imitating how it would be

01:38:25.110 --> 01:38:26.800
to play with two players.

01:38:26.800 --> 01:38:30.760 position:56%
So I mean he's just a virtuoso, but
if you put him together with someone

01:38:30.760 --> 01:38:34.900
like Ford Kwinda [Assumed
Spelling] I mean things are really

01:38:34.900 --> 01:38:37.300
just unbelievable.

01:38:37.300 --> 01:38:46.380
You have to tune into it for a
long time before you really get

01:38:46.380 --> 01:38:49.790
at what's going on there.

01:38:49.790 --> 01:38:55.580
These are all night spirit
possession ceremonies and so on.

01:38:55.580 --> 01:38:58.370
After awhile it does feel

01:38:58.370 --> 01:39:01.040
like everything is just
sort of automated, right?

01:39:02.260 --> 01:39:12.060
It's other worldly in that sense,
but Gwanzuto is just a brilliant,

01:39:12.060 --> 01:39:18.680
brilliant, brilliant player and he
made this recording because he came

01:39:18.680 --> 01:39:21.100
and took a visit to
the United States.

01:39:21.100 --> 01:39:23.660
And you know that's what you do,
you have your CD in your pocket

01:39:23.660 --> 01:39:24.960
and then you do your
concert and so on.

01:39:24.960 --> 01:39:27.700
But traditionally you
never play with one player,

01:39:27.700 --> 01:39:30.850 position:56%
I mean in the context of mbira or an
all-night ceremony you always play

01:39:30.850 --> 01:39:32.940
with a second player
who is locking in,

01:39:32.940 --> 01:39:34.920
so that the whole thing
becomes much more mysterious

01:39:34.920 --> 01:39:36.570
and phantom patterns can emerge.

01:39:36.570 --> 01:39:38.690
But, yes, a great player.

01:39:38.690 --> 01:39:39.990
I think, yes, sorry?

01:39:39.990 --> 01:39:47.370
&gt;&gt; How are we spelling, if I heard
you correctly, the Angolan tusona?

01:39:47.370 --> 01:39:49.460
&gt;&gt; Martin Scherzinger:
Yes, t-u-s-o-n-a.

01:39:49.460 --> 01:39:50.760
So a short question.

01:39:50.760 --> 01:39:56.040
&gt;&gt; And also the mbira in that other
slide was I think on the right,

01:39:56.040 --> 01:39:59.050
I wonder where the
other one [inaudible]?

01:39:59.050 --> 01:40:00.350
&gt;&gt; Martin Scherzinger: Yes, okay,

01:40:00.350 --> 01:40:04.830
that is called matepe,
m-a-t-e-p-e, matepe.

01:40:04.830 --> 01:40:09.550
Matepe is, in fact, from the
perspective of fractal logic

01:40:09.550 --> 01:40:11.780
that I've been working with,

01:40:11.780 --> 01:40:15.920
an even more interesting
instrument than the [inaudible].

01:40:15.920 --> 01:40:17.510
It is less played than
the [inaudible]

01:40:17.510 --> 01:40:21.870
because it's basically what was
once known as the Korekrre people,

01:40:21.870 --> 01:40:23.170
which is a dialect of
Shauna [Assumed Spelling].

01:40:23.170 --> 01:40:24.520
It's actually an independent
language,

01:40:24.520 --> 01:40:25.820
but history has it that ...

01:40:25.820 --> 01:40:27.120
&gt;&gt; Korikori?

01:40:27.120 --> 01:40:28.420
&gt;&gt; Martin Scherzinger:
K-o-r-e-k-r-r-e.

01:40:28.420 --> 01:40:29.720
Very few matepe playing
families left in the world,

01:40:29.720 --> 01:40:31.020
but that is I think the Korekrre
region is up in northeast

01:40:31.020 --> 01:40:32.320
of Zimbabwe or modern day Zimbabwe,

01:40:32.320 --> 01:40:33.620
an area that once controlled
the salt pan,

01:40:33.620 --> 01:40:34.920
which for a landlocked land
is gold, I mean you need salt.

01:40:34.920 --> 01:40:36.220
And it was once in my view a
very dominant area culturally

01:40:36.220 --> 01:40:37.520
and then became in some sense
impoverished through the forces

01:40:37.520 --> 01:40:38.820 position:56%
of history, let's just call it that.

01:40:38.820 --> 01:40:40.120
And as a result of that the
instrument is marginal today even

01:40:40.120 --> 01:40:41.420
in Zimbabwe, which is really
interesting and kind of problematic

01:40:41.420 --> 01:40:42.720
because it is I think the source
of much of the fractal reasoning

01:40:42.720 --> 01:40:44.020
in harmonies, but that was
a different conversation

01:40:44.020 --> 01:40:45.320
but it's a fascinating instrument.

01:40:45.320 --> 01:40:46.620
Okay, one more question?

01:40:46.620 --> 01:40:47.920
&gt;&gt; How different is the
matepe to the mbira?

01:40:47.920 --> 01:40:49.220
&gt;&gt; Martin Scherzinger:
The mbira [inaudible]?

01:40:49.220 --> 01:40:50.520
&gt;&gt; Yes, because you said in the
center you have your low notes

01:40:50.520 --> 01:40:51.820
and the high notes on the side?

01:40:51.820 --> 01:40:53.120
&gt;&gt; Martin Scherzinger: Yes, so
that basic principle is the same,

01:40:53.120 --> 01:40:54.420
but you'll see all of the
notes, the note configuration --

01:40:54.420 --> 01:40:55.720
there are many more notes here,
first of all, in most of them

01:40:55.720 --> 01:40:57.020
and then they're organized
very differently.

01:40:57.020 --> 01:40:58.320
[ Inaudible ]

01:40:58.320 --> 01:40:59.620
&gt;&gt; Martin Scherzinger: If
you can play the matepe

01:40:59.620 --> 01:41:01.350
that would be the place to go
because the mbira [inaudible],

01:41:01.350 --> 01:41:03.880
here's the tragedy, remember
I mentioned radio, too,

01:41:03.880 --> 01:41:06.890
where they were recording made
for Africans to keep Africans

01:41:06.890 --> 01:41:09.570
in separate developed space,
you know, so radio, too?

01:41:09.570 --> 01:41:13.410
Well, the mbira [inaudible]
the one on the right happens

01:41:13.410 --> 01:41:16.170
to be the instrument
that was the most played

01:41:16.170 --> 01:41:19.500 position:56%
in the Colonial center then called
Salzbury and the engineers didn't go

01:41:19.500 --> 01:41:22.540
that far, and so there's a great
archive of mbira [inaudible]

01:41:22.540 --> 01:41:25.170
and the matepe sort of
gets written out of history

01:41:25.170 --> 01:41:27.390
because it's a little
too far away to travel

01:41:27.390 --> 01:41:30.510
so there's fewer historical
recordings.

01:41:30.510 --> 01:41:35.060
[ Inaudible ]

01:41:35.060 --> 01:41:36.360
&gt;&gt; Martin Scherzinger: Yes, Stella
Chuwachi [Assumed Spelling].

01:41:36.360 --> 01:41:37.660
&gt;&gt; Is she still playing?

01:41:37.660 --> 01:41:40.690
Because I saw her here,
there was some program,

01:41:40.690 --> 01:41:45.250
and I can't remember the
name and it was all women.

01:41:45.250 --> 01:41:50.910
She and [inaudible] and others
and it was really extraordinary.

01:41:50.910 --> 01:41:56.430
And they say she had to fight
to be able to play the mbira

01:41:56.430 --> 01:41:58.470
because it's traditionally
played by a man.

01:41:58.470 --> 01:42:00.170
&gt;&gt; Martin Scherzinger: Yes, it's
a sort of patriarchal thing,

01:42:00.170 --> 01:42:01.980
but there have been some
great woman performers.

01:42:01.980 --> 01:42:05.430
I mean Beulah Dyoko, who died
recently, but she traveled

01:42:05.430 --> 01:42:08.870
with some really great
players in the '90s.

01:42:08.870 --> 01:42:12.930
Beulah D-y-o-k-o, she died
recently, but a magnificent player.

01:42:12.930 --> 01:42:14.590
I think perhaps better than Stella.

01:42:14.590 --> 01:42:17.430
Stella is kind of a
little more hybridized.

01:42:17.430 --> 01:42:21.430
But, yes, it's a constantly
evolving tradition.

01:42:21.430 --> 01:42:23.690 position:56%
But the one thing that's interesting
is that, as I said earlier,

01:42:23.690 --> 01:42:26.650
as a technology it didn't
change much, like the piano,

01:42:26.650 --> 01:42:29.810
it sort of settled down towards
the end of the 18th Century

01:42:29.810 --> 01:42:31.360
and then it reached
its talus, right?

01:42:31.360 --> 01:42:35.090
I mean it tweaked a little bit,
but the basic technical art lay,

01:42:35.090 --> 01:42:39.080
the interface design remained the
same and it's that that becomes

01:42:39.080 --> 01:42:42.530
such an instructive
microscope into history.

01:42:42.530 --> 01:42:48.060
&gt;&gt; You talked about how
the music was created.

01:42:48.060 --> 01:42:52.780
My question is what did
the dancers do with this?

01:42:52.780 --> 01:42:55.490
Can you look at one
of these diagrams

01:42:55.490 --> 01:42:59.760
and know what the dancers
would be doing?

01:42:59.760 --> 01:43:01.950
&gt;&gt; Martin Scherzinger: Okay, so
the dancers do different things

01:43:01.950 --> 01:43:05.340
in different places, obviously,
but take for example --

01:43:05.340 --> 01:43:07.980
I'll just have to be
brief so I'm just going

01:43:07.980 --> 01:43:09.990
to give you an interesting
sort of schematic.

01:43:09.990 --> 01:43:12.500
Remember we started with the
gankogui pipes from Mozambique,

01:43:12.500 --> 01:43:17.940
which was the second thing we did,
but the dancers there remember move

01:43:17.940 --> 01:43:20.870
in a way that the instrumentalists
are not playing, right?

01:43:20.870 --> 01:43:22.320
So they're going one,
two, three, one, two,

01:43:22.320 --> 01:43:24.670
three, yafu, yafu, yafu, yafu.

01:43:24.670 --> 01:43:27.420
And then once that is locked in,
once that felt beat is locked in,

01:43:27.420 --> 01:43:29.440
then there are all sorts
of dancers with steps,

01:43:29.440 --> 01:43:31.480
such as 50 Boro [Assumed
Spelling], which is a football.

01:43:31.480 --> 01:43:35.000
But you're feeling it in
four, so you're not doing --

01:43:35.000 --> 01:43:38.430
it's a bit boring, but you
are feeling it in four.

01:43:38.430 --> 01:43:41.490
In the context of the mbira,
which is sort of on, off, on,

01:43:41.490 --> 01:43:43.400
off, on, off, binary, right?

01:43:43.400 --> 01:43:45.820
Daka, daka, daka, daka,
daka, daka --

01:43:45.820 --> 01:43:47.350
and that's kind of basic principle.

01:43:47.350 --> 01:43:50.220
I mean here's a diagram
that makes that apparent.

01:43:50.220 --> 01:43:53.670
This is if everybody is
playing exactly the same thing.

01:43:53.670 --> 01:43:55.670
So ding, dong, ding,
dong, ding, dong.

01:43:55.670 --> 01:43:57.820
And the other one ding,
dong, and so but what comes

01:43:57.820 --> 01:44:00.460
to the ear is da, ta,
da, ta, da, ta.

01:44:00.460 --> 01:44:03.840
Interestingly, what
the [inaudible] does,

01:44:03.840 --> 01:44:08.200
which guides the dance step is not
going da, ta, da, ta, da, ta --

01:44:08.200 --> 01:44:11.230
now the music is in four, one,
two, three, four, one, two, three,

01:44:11.230 --> 01:44:15.710 position:56%
four -- it's binary, that's why,
but the [inaudible] goes choo, choo,

01:44:15.710 --> 01:44:18.660
choo, choo, choo, choo, choo,
choo, it's in ternary, right?

01:44:18.660 --> 01:44:21.480
And the dancers are going
to move in ternary time.

01:44:21.480 --> 01:44:24.320
So it's kind of cutting across
that again and, of course,

01:44:24.320 --> 01:44:28.760
the dancers become complex but
the basic felt pulse is at,

01:44:28.760 --> 01:44:30.950
how should we say, at
a kind of cross-current

01:44:30.950 --> 01:44:34.130
with the dominant musical
input, okay?

01:44:34.130 --> 01:44:37.070
Again, I don't want to
generalize this Continent.

01:44:37.070 --> 01:44:39.170
There are certain features,
you know, it's interesting

01:44:39.170 --> 01:44:42.670
because even just the Nyungwe,
which is close to the [inaudible].

01:44:42.670 --> 01:44:45.670
I mean we've just got a
simple Colonial border,

01:44:45.670 --> 01:44:49.110
almost a straight line
separating them, so they're related

01:44:49.110 --> 01:44:51.900
but they've inverted
that relationship

01:44:51.900 --> 01:44:55.500 position:56%
of in the one we've got four against
three, in the other we've got three

01:44:55.500 --> 01:44:58.740
against four, broadly speaking
when it comes to the dance.

01:44:58.740 --> 01:45:01.080
But the question of dance
is much bigger than this

